00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:38.180
So a trust and safety crash course I always say it's

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:40.850
all the bad stuff that can happen on the internet.

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:44.490
But with a caveat that online and offline are no longer completely

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:45.260
separate worlds.

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:48.260
The harms you experience online translate into offline harms.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:50.880
With things like ride sharing, with things like rentals,

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:54.580
anything that happens online can also mean something that happens in the

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:56.120
physical, tangible world.

00:03:56.140 --> 00:04:01.250
But trust and safety really refers to teams, technologies, and

00:04:01.250 --> 00:04:05.780
just the general field of studying online harms, responding to them

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:06.380
as well.

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:09.740
Fun fact, this term actually was originated by eBay a number

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:10.420
of years ago.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:12.550
If you look at the Wikipedia page on trust and safety,

00:04:12.550 --> 00:04:13.180
I wrote it.

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:16.430
So it has a nice little history about how this field really

00:04:16.490 --> 00:04:18.220
came to be and where it's going today.

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:21.500
It can include things, like I said earlier, user abuse

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:24.560
reporting, any kind of flagging, any kind of customer

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:27.850
support flow, saying something happened to me on this platform or

00:04:27.850 --> 00:04:29.800
in this experience that I do not like.

00:04:29.820 --> 00:04:33.680
It can also include things around online child safety and abuse and

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:36.200
exploitation, things around CSAM.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:39.540
A lot of people on the internet used to say CP.

00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:43.340
We as an industry are moving away from that because pornography involves

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:44.820
consent sensing adults.

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:46.370
Children cannot consent.

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:48.840
So we refer to it as CSAM, child sexual abuse

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:49.820
materials.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:51.830
It also includes things like radicalization.

00:04:51.830 --> 00:04:54.540
This can be things around glorifying mass casualty events,

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:58.380
things school shootings, things mass shootings, things around kind of

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:02.040
like really harmful narratives that can lead to potential mass casualty

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:02.780
events.

00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:05.670
Things around harassment, things around non-consensual intimate

00:05:05.670 --> 00:05:06.300
imagery.

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:10.970
Like I mentioned, anything bad that can happen on the internet

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:11.500
.

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:14.380
And a lot of the former speakers throughout the atmosphere conference have

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:17.580
said, it also includes things around information influence campaigns.

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:20.890
And some of the labelers that Julia talked about earlier also

00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:25.260
cover topics around things like zoophilia amongst certain communities that

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:27.580
are very prominent and active on atmosphere.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:29.340
Zoophilia is still not allowed.

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:32.700
So with that fun slide, we're going to move into

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:36.030
more formally what trust and safety really means.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:38.460
And I do like the call out here of trust and safety

00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:40.930
is not just about punishing or negative effects.

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:43.160
It is also about encouraging pro-social behavior.

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:45.100
So there's a lot of different aspects.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:47.260
And I want to give a shout out to both Dr.

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:49.740
K and Julie, who talked about kind of like all kind

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:51.990
of trust and safety work, moderation work, labeling work is

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:53.180
inherently political.

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:56.300
The values will change based on the demographics of those teams.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:06:00.200
Ideally, you have a team with very mixed demographics and backgrounds

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:00.360
.

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:02.220
What we've seen in a lot of companies, a lot

00:06:02.350 --> 00:06:05.110
of teams, is those teams becoming very, very white and

00:06:05.110 --> 00:06:06.780
very, very former cops.

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:10.270
That's going to influence how trust and safety is done on

00:06:10.270 --> 00:06:11.400
those platforms.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:13.520
But it should not be about policing.

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:15.640
It should not be about what comes down.

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:17.330
It should also be about what is going up.

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:19.960
What are you putting in front of people to encourage that pro

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:22.140
-social behavior?

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:25.740
And now into the academic stuff.

00:06:25.740 --> 00:06:28.380
While we were first incubating Roost, we did so

00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:31.970
doing research at Columbia University's Institute of Global Politics.

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:34.480
We found that in academic studies, there was pretty much no

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:37.530
mention of the tools that platforms actually use to do this kind

00:06:37.540 --> 00:06:39.100
of trust and safety work.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:41.440
A lot of stuff about the sociology, the policy, maybe

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:44.450
the operations, and of course, the trauma and wellness that

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:47.160
it takes on the working class people that do this work.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:48.940
But nothing on the technology.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:49.980
So we wrote a paper.

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:52.400
We talked to over 50 different trust and safety, anti-

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.150
abuse, and risk teams across startups, non-profit

00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:57.380
organizations, major tech companies.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:06:59.260
And these people were very open.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:02.420
And what we found is that everyone's tools look the same

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:02.620
.

00:07:02.620 --> 00:07:04.060
Doesn't matter if you're a marketplace.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:05.260
Doesn't matter if you're a cruising app.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.710
It doesn't matter if you're a traditional social media app

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:07.900
.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:09.500
All of your tools are the same.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:13.140
So we came up with a framework called dire because the situation

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:13.660
is dire.

00:07:13.660 --> 00:07:15.420
D, detection.

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:16.380
This could be a user report.

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:17.420
It could be a classifier.

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:18.460
It could be hash matching.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:20.140
How do you know that something's up?

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:23.330
Once you find something is up, how do you investigate it

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:23.480
?

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:25.740
How do you know is this the only thing that is up

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:25.980
?

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:29.020
Are there other things that are going on with this particular signal

00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:29.260
?

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:33.080
So let's say maybe there's a signal sharing group.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.250
Maybe it's literally on signal.

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:38.560
And someone says this IP address is associated with a Russian propaganda

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:39.260
campaign.

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:41.970
You want to know is this happening on my project?

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:43.690
Is this happening on my platform?

00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:45.400
That's where investigation takes place.

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.020
It's supposed to be more open-ended.

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:49.600
You need to understand what is the scale and scope of some

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:51.420
of the things that are happening.

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:54.020
Once you find all that stuff, you have to review it

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:54.200
.

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:57.420
Special shout out to Acorn, the moderation tool built and

00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:59.800
designed by Black Sky, Ozone, by the Blue Sky

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:00.220
team.

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:02.780
We're going to talk about Coop, our review tool

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:03.080
.

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:05.270
It's designed for scaled, flexible review.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:08.380
How do you have the right context to take into consideration whether

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:10.540
something's actually violating or not?

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:11.650
Finally, enforcement.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:13.020
What are the actions available?

00:08:13.020 --> 00:08:14.650
Maybe an action is taking content down.

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:15.950
Maybe it's sending them a warning.

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:18.940
Maybe it's sending them a kind of like, what is

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:19.740
it called?

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:22.630
A de-radicalizing kind of like resource of here

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:26.470
's some stuff to read because you're searching something that might

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:27.630
mean something else.

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.540
And this also includes reporting to different authorities.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:34.170
Authorities here does not always mean police or law enforcement.

00:08:34.170 --> 00:08:36.940
It can mean organizations like NECMEC, the National

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:38.700
Center for Missing and Exploited Children.

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:41.660
In the US, there are a subset of laws that say

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:44.140
, "If you become aware of things like CSAM,

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:47.930
you are legally required to report it to organizations like NEC

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:50.540
MEC." And if that tiny QR code is too hard

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:53.020
to scan, there's a big QR code for the paper

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:53.020
.

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:54.850
If you want to read our paper, it is right here

00:08:54.850 --> 00:08:55.020
.

00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:58.220
You can also just look for the Dyer framework and you

00:08:58.220 --> 00:08:59.100
should find it.

00:09:00.860 --> 00:09:02.140
Kind of talked about this a bit.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:05.740
So yeah, we found that platforms are constantly reinventing these

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:06.140
tools.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:08.180
And a lot of times they're, you know, it

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:09.980
's internal tools at different organizations.

00:09:09.980 --> 00:09:12.140
So that's part of the part of the thing we're

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:12.940
trying to solve.

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:19.290
I have personally built or worked on review tools at three different

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:19.690
places.

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:22.540
They all look and act the same and they all have the

00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:23.410
same features.

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:25.260
It's a waste of engineering time.

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:26.860
It's a waste of resources.

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:29.500
And we all have the same feature requests and bugs.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:33.100
This is helpful as well.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:35.520
These are some of the terms that we've, you've

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:38.020
probably been hearing us say, and you may hear us continue

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:38.460
to say.

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:39.980
Yeah.

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:42.620
I kind of covered this one already as well.

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:44.140
Yeah.

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:44.220
And...

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:45.900
Oh, yes.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:48.770
So a phrase that we often say is, "Roost

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:51.720
is tools, not rules." Or better, tools for your

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:54.780
rules, because we're not in charge of creating policy.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:56.860
We got this, we got a lot of people asking us

00:09:56.860 --> 00:09:58.180
like, "Can you write our policies for us?" It

00:09:58.180 --> 00:10:00.140
's like, "No, we cannot." We are not

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.230
only, we are, a lot of us have worked in

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:06.060
policy roles, but every single community is different.

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:08.990
We're probably not members of your specific community.

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.650
So we don't know what are the norms and the,

00:10:11.650 --> 00:10:14.920
what's acceptable behavior within your own community.

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:18.170
Our, and some of this can really change based on jurisdiction

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:18.300
.

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:20.790
The example we have here is that in the US, there

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:25.280
's no mandatory requirement to go voluntarily look for CSAM.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:27.530
But if you do find it, you do have to report

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:29.630
it to NECMEC and then preserve data for up

00:10:29.630 --> 00:10:30.370
to a year.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:33.350
Versus if you're in the UK, platforms just have

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:35.660
to remove and report it immediately.

00:10:35.660 --> 00:10:39.040
And it's enforced by regulator that has teeth in that they

00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:40.140
will find you.

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:43.230
So the big difference there is that data retention.

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:46.290
I've talked to, you know, regulators or organizations of

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:47.720
the UK who are like, "Hey, like, isn

