Some of you may have known all this already and you're

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:38.460
saying finally we're actually going to see the project.

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:40.520
So Coop, this is the review tool.

00:16:40.520 --> 00:16:42.300
What we did as Roost and again we're a non

00:16:42.300 --> 00:16:42.860
-profit.

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:45.500
We wanted to bootstrap some of our software projects so

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:49.540
we acquired the IP from a startup that was selling trust and

00:16:49.540 --> 00:16:52.370
safety tools as a service and we bought it.

00:16:52.370 --> 00:16:55.270
And then we worked over the past six to eight months to

00:16:55.270 --> 00:16:57.740
refactor that code to make it open sourceable.

00:16:57.740 --> 00:16:58.510
We're not done.

00:16:58.510 --> 00:17:00.970
There's still a lot of really messy legacy tech that that

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:02.930
's in this code base but that's the fun part of

00:17:02.930 --> 00:17:03.940
working in the open.

00:17:04.040 --> 00:17:05.940
We wanted the v0 out there to be like hey like

00:17:05.940 --> 00:17:09.300
what's we know we need to prioritize certain migrations,

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:11.640
database cleanup, simplifications overall.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:14.130
What else is needed from the community?

00:17:14.130 --> 00:17:15.500
So again we want your opinions.

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:19.980
So Coop, it is built for manual review.

00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:22.770
It also has like an auto bot directly built in.

00:17:22.770 --> 00:17:25.890
This is self-hosted on your own infrastructure.

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:29.490
It comes with reviewer wellness features such as blurring,

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:32.060
grayscale, and auto muting of videos.

00:17:32.060 --> 00:17:34.280
I'm going to go into a more comprehensive demo as well

00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:34.460
.

00:17:34.610 --> 00:17:36.660
And like I said there's automation rules built in.

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:38.790
There's two types of rules within Coop.

00:17:38.790 --> 00:17:41.310
One is the proactive kind of auto moderation.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:45.010
Like you know something is bad or you know how to action

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:45.270
it.

00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:47.090
Your team doesn't need to keep doing it.

00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:48.520
You can set that up as a rule.

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.280
The second rule, the second type of rule is the routing

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:51.700
rule.

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:53.580
So as things are coming in, let's say you're

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:56.230
ingesting a million reports to your label of service or to

00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:58.460
your moderation service, you need to sort them.

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:01.660
Because from a wellness perspective, if you put all those reports

00:18:01.660 --> 00:18:04.220
and tasks into a certain queue, into a single queue,

00:18:04.220 --> 00:18:06.220
you don't know what's coming up next.

00:18:06.220 --> 00:18:10.510
And context switching between something like harassment or hate to something like

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:13.020
NSFW, cartoons, that's a lot for your

00:18:13.020 --> 00:18:14.100
brain to do.

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:15.750
That's going to impact you a lot more.

00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:18.250
So assigning it to specific queues, and you can also

00:18:18.250 --> 00:18:19.650
do that based on language.

00:18:19.650 --> 00:18:22.260
If you're providing services for a global set of user base

00:18:22.270 --> 00:18:24.460
, you want to have someone who's fluent in that language

00:18:24.460 --> 00:18:26.190
, who has that cultural context, to then go in and

00:18:26.190 --> 00:18:26.700
review.

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:29.960
Some of the main features.

00:18:29.960 --> 00:18:33.930
Coop is the very first free, open source, end

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:36.420
-to-end child safety tool, which means it provides

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:37.970
hash matching for known CSAM.

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:40.680
You still have to go get your own credentials from NEC

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.010
MEC, but once you have that, you can just

00:18:43.010 --> 00:18:46.510
plug it in and start matching against databases of known CSAM

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:50.360
that have already been validated and verified by experts like NEC

00:18:50.360 --> 00:18:50.860
MEC.

00:18:50.860 --> 00:18:53.660
We also integrated it with Google's content safety API.

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:55.320
This is not free like open source.

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:56.850
It's free like free beer.

00:18:56.860 --> 00:18:57.690
It's a free API.

00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:00.430
You, again, need to get your own credentials from Google

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:00.700
.

00:19:00.700 --> 00:19:03.220
This is a novel CSAM detector.

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:06.400
This classifier can find CSAM that has not yet been

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:09.260
hashed, which is an increasing area of harm in the

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:11.010
child safety landscape today.

00:19:11.010 --> 00:19:13.000
And we have it built in to support NECMEC

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:13.900
reporting.

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:16.070
We've integrated it with NECMEC's CyberT

00:19:16.070 --> 00:19:19.040
ip reporting API as well as their hash sharing API, so

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:21.590
that way as you find CSAM, you can report it

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:25.180
to the authorities with the right amount of detail that makes it

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:27.340
actually actionable.

00:19:27.340 --> 00:19:28.680
It's scalable for your org.

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:31.170
Like I mentioned earlier, you can have multiple queues for

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:34.030
different types of workflows, different types of categories.

00:19:34.030 --> 00:19:36.110
It's also a multi-tenant code base, because

00:19:36.110 --> 00:19:38.220
, again, it was originally a SaaS startup.

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:41.900
So if you have maybe like a, so let's say

00:19:41.900 --> 00:19:45.560
like you want to have multiple completely separate instances of coop with

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:48.710
totally separate people working in those workflows, you can also set

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:49.500
it up like that.

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:52.140
And I talked a little bit about the routing rules and proactive

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:52.700
rules.

00:19:52.700 --> 00:19:55.350
There's also a unique kind of like architecture that we built

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:55.660
in.

00:19:55.660 --> 00:19:58.940
We plugified everything, so that way any kind of signal

00:19:58.940 --> 00:20:01.820
, model, detection service that you're using, you can

00:20:01.820 --> 00:20:03.660
actually integrate it directly into coop.

00:20:03.660 --> 00:20:06.620
Coop comes with three pre-built API integrations.

00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:09.510
Google's content safety API, like I mentioned already.

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:13.080
OpenAI's moderation API, just because realistically we know a

00:20:13.170 --> 00:20:14.270
lot of people depend on it.

00:20:14.270 --> 00:20:15.010
It is free.

00:20:15.070 --> 00:20:16.700
You have to get your API token from OpenAI.

00:20:16.700 --> 00:20:19.340
And it supports image and text.

00:20:19.340 --> 00:20:21.100
And third one is Zentropy.

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:23.750
You may have heard some folks at Atmosphere talking about

00:20:23.780 --> 00:20:24.410
Zentropy.

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:27.660
They have open weight models, but for coop, we integrated

00:20:27.660 --> 00:20:30.040
with the API, which again, is backed by that open

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:32.060
weight model for text classification.

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:35.340
This is essentially, you can design your own text classifier

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:35.580
.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:39.050
You write a policy prompt in Zentropy, it creates a

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:40.300
model for you.

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:43.720
It is completely tunable, completely customizable, and it's

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:46.060
a small model that runs really well with latency.

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:48.900
So if you need something that's happening near real time,

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:50.920
Zentropy might be a good option for you.

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:56.300
So, for the different types of people that are building on

00:20:56.300 --> 00:20:58.620
AppProto, here's where you might use coop.

